Abstract

Diabetic retinopathy (DR) screening requires models that are data‑efficient, interpretable, and deployable on edge devices. We prove that, under the stated conditions of near‑optimal initialization and concentration on a low‑dimensional posterior, conditioning a deep network on multifractal spectra f(\alpha), \Delta\alpha and lacunarity \Lambda(r) reduces PAC‑Bayesian sample complexity from O(d/\epsilon^2) to O(D_f/\epsilon^2), where D_f \ll d is the data manifold’s Minkowski dimension. We design FracFormer, an 8.3 MB INT8 multimodal architecture fusing fundus + OCT‑A via cross‑attention to multifractal features, with explicit failure flags when theoretical assumptions are violated. We provide a Predetermined Change Control Plan for FDA and EU AI Act compliance treating fractal biomarkers as explanation artifacts. All datasets are public; no physical testing is performed.

