Chapter 1: Introduction

1.1 Problem Statement

Let \mathcal{X}_f \subset \mathbb{R}^{H\times W \times 3} be fundus images and \mathcal{X}_o \subset \mathbb{R}^{1\times H\times W} be OCT‑A en face slabs (single channel, 224×224). Let \mathcal{Y}=\{0,1,2,3,4\} be DR grades R0 (no DR) through R4 (proliferative DR). The task is to learn a predictor h: \mathcal{X}_f \times \mathcal{X}_o \to \mathcal{Y} that minimizes the risk R(h)=\mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim\mathcal{D}}[\ell(h(x),y)] (with \ell the cross‑entropy loss) subject to:

· C1 (data efficiency): n_{\text{train}} \leq 10^4 for reliable R0 vs. R1 separation.
· C2 (model size): \text{size}(h) \leq 10 MB after INT8 quantization.
· C3 (interpretability): h outputs clinically interpretable biomarkers: box‑counting dimension D_0, multifractal width \Delta\alpha, and lacunarity \Lambda(r) at r=5,10,20 pixels.
· C4 (self‑diagnostic): h provides a flag \in \{\text{OK}, \text{UNRELIABLE}\} indicating whether the theoretical generalization guarantees apply.

1.2 Research Hypothesis

H1: There exists a feature map \Phi: \mathcal{X}_f \to \mathbb{R}^{18} computing multifractal‑lacunarity vector \phi such that conditioning the predictor h on \phi(x) reduces the data‑dependent fractal dimension d_Q of the posterior distribution Q over network weights. Under the condition \|w-w_0\|^2 \leq B (where w_0 is a pretrained initialization), this yields tighter PAC‑Bayesian generalization bounds without Lipschitz assumptions on h.

We explicitly do not claim that fractal dimension universally predicts generalization. Consistent with NeurIPS 2024 findings (Tan et al.), fractal measures can be confounded by hyperparameters and fail under poor initialization. Our self‑diagnostic flag directly addresses this limitation.

1.3 Contributions

The thesis makes the following original contributions:

1. Theory (Theorem 3.1): A Lipschitz‑free PAC‑Bayesian generalization bound that uses a data‑dependent fractal dimension d_Q. The bound includes an operational condition: if \|w-w_0\|^2 exceeds a threshold, the model flags its own prediction as unreliable.
2. Mathematics (Definition 3.4): A 18‑dimensional feature vector \phi combining 2D‑MFDFA generalized Hurst exponents h(q) (q=-5,\dots,5), box‑counting dimension D_0, multifractal width \Delta\alpha, and lacunarity \Lambda_5,\Lambda_{10},\Lambda_{20}. Clinical justification: \Lambda + D_0 has higher specificity than D_0 alone in microvascular disease.
