Chapter 2: Related Work

We survey prior work in four areas: multifractal analysis for medical imaging, deep learning for DR screening, theoretical generalization bounds for deep networks, and regulatory frameworks for AI as a medical device.

Multifractal analysis in retinal imaging: Early work applied box‑counting to vessel skeletons for DR screening. More recently, Diagnostics (Basel) 2025 reported 98.01% accuracy for early DR detection using multifractal features from OCT images with a multilayer perceptron. Lacunarity has been shown to improve specificity for microvascular impairments (2019‑2023 studies). However, no prior work combines 2D‑MFDFA with lacunarity in a deep learning pipeline.

Deep learning for DR: End‑to‑end CNNs (e.g., ResNet‑50, Inception‑v3) achieve high AUC on large datasets but require >50k images for R0 vs. R1 and output saliency maps that are not accepted by FDA as explanation. EdgeRetina (2024) achieved 8.27 MB, 15.43 ms latency, 90.7% sensitivity with dynamic threshold calibration (71.4% FP reduction). Multimodal approaches (fundus + OCT‑A) remain rare; a 2026 graph‑enhanced fusion paper reported 93.8% accuracy on MESSIDOR‑2 and >98% on EyePACS, but without fractal conditioning.

Theoretical generalization bounds: PAC‑Bayes bounds (Catoni, McAllester) provide data‑dependent guarantees. Dupuis et al. (ICML 2023) introduced data‑dependent fractal dimensions and proved generalization bounds without Lipschitz assumptions. Tan et al. (NeurIPS 2024) showed that fractal measures can fail under poor initialization, which we address via a self‑diagnostic flag.

Regulatory: FDA issued final PCCP guidance in August 2025; Axial3D received the first PCCP clearance for an image segmentation AI. EU AI Act (effective 2024) classifies medical AI as high‑risk, with Annex I systems required to comply by 2 August 2028 (Digital Omnibus extension, Nov 2025).

Novelty statement: This thesis is the first to unify:
(1) Lipschitz‑free fractal PAC‑Bayes bounds (Dupuis et al. framework),
(2) 2D‑MFDFA + lacunarity feature extraction,
(3) multimodal fundus + OCT‑A cross‑attention,
(4) <10 MB edge deployment with dynamic calibration,
(5) self‑diagnostic flagging for theoretical reliability, and
(6) regulator‑aligned explanation design (PCCP, EU AI Act).

