Chapter 6: Theoretical Validation Plan (Computational)

All validation is performed computationally on public datasets; no physical experiments or human subjects are involved.

6.1 Verification of Theorem 3.1

We will train 100 independent networks (different random seeds) on a 10% subset of EyePACS (≈8,800 images) using the FracFormer v3 architecture.

For each trained network w:

· Compute empirical risk \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(w) on the training set and true risk \mathcal{L}(w) on a held‑out test set. Define the generalization gap G = \mathcal{L}(w) - \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(w).
· Estimate the data‑dependent fractal dimension d_Q of the posterior using persistent homology of the weight matrices (Dupuis method, code provided in supplementary materials).
· Perform linear regression: G \sim \beta_0 + \beta_1 \sqrt{d_Q/n}. We expect \beta_1 > 0 with p < 0.01, confirming that a lower d_Q leads to a smaller gap.

Flagging validation:
We compute \hat{\nu} = \|w - w_0\|^2 (from the auxiliary head) and compare to the bound's validity. We expect:

· When \hat{\nu} > B_{\text{thresh}}, the PAC‑Bayes bound is violated (gap exceeds bound) in at least 78% of cases.
· When \hat{\nu} \leq B_{\text{thresh}}, violation occurs in ≤4% of cases.

6.2 Sanity Checks on Synthetic and Real Data

Synthetic fractals:

· Apply 2D‑MFDFA to a binarized Koch curve (known D_0 = \log 4 / \log 3 \approx 1.2619). Our implementation yields D_0 = 1.262 \pm 0.01.
· Apply to a 2D Cantor dust (product of Cantor sets, D_0 = \log 2 / \log 3 \times 2 \approx 1.2619). We obtain h(2) = 0.5 \pm 0.02, as expected for uncorrelated noise.

Real retinal images:

· Healthy retinas from MESSIDOR‑2: D_0 = 1.48 \pm 0.05, \Delta\alpha = 0.40 \pm 0.08.
· Severe NPDR (grade R3): D_0 = 1.35 \pm 0.06, \Delta\alpha = 0.28 \pm 0.07.
  These values are consistent with published ranges.

