Chapter 7: Regulatory and Ethical Design

7.1 FDA Strategy

Device classification: The proposed software is an AI/ML‑enabled Software as a Medical Device (SaMD) intended for screening of diabetic retinopathy. It falls under Class II, product code POK (Ophthalmic Computer‑Aided Detection). Because we output biomarkers D_0, \Delta\alpha, \Lambda as explanation artifacts (21 CFR 892.2050) rather than primary diagnostic outputs, the regulatory burden is reduced.

Predetermined Change Control Plan (PCCP):
Per FDA’s final guidance (August 2025), we submit a PCCP describing planned modifications and the validation methodology. The following table summarizes the plan:

Modification Verification Validation Impact Assessment
Add a new OCT‑A device model (different acquisition parameters) Run inference on 100 representative volumes; check that \phi extraction succeeds Compare AUC for referable DR against reference device; require \Delta\text{AUC} < 0.02 Low – no retraining needed
Update MFDFA q range from [-5,5] to [-7,7] Recompute \phi on validation set; verify numerical stability Re‑run ablation study on DM1‑156; require \Deltasensitivity < 1% Moderate – re‑validate on DM1‑156
Retrain model on new data (less than 30% increase in training set size) Full training pipeline on 80% of new+old data Hold‑out test set from new distribution; require \DeltaAUC < 0.02 and sensitivity ≥90% High – full re‑validation required

Explanation artifacts: The model outputs D_0, \Delta\alpha, \Lambda with reference ranges (e.g., healthy: D_0 > 1.45, DR: D_0 < 1.40). These are displayed to the clinician but are not used as the sole basis for diagnosis. This approach aligns with the FDA’s preference for transparent AI.

7.2 EU AI Act

Under the EU AI Act (Regulation (EU) 2024/1689), our system is classified as high‑risk under Annex I (medical devices). Compliance is required by 2 August 2028 (extension granted by the Digital Omnibus proposal, November 2025). Our compliance roadmap includes:

· Technical documentation following ISO 13485:2016 (Quality management systems for medical devices).
· Risk management per ISO 14971:2019 (application of risk management to medical devices).
· Post‑market monitoring plan (continuous collection of real‑world performance data).
· Human oversight via the biomarker display – a clinician can override the AI’s screening recommendation based on the fractal values.

We will maintain a conformity assessment with a notified body; the self‑diagnostic flag (OK/UNRELIABLE) serves as a safety mechanism.

7.3 Data Ethics

All datasets used are public and have been obtained under their respective research licenses (e.g., EyePACS Kaggle license, MESSIDOR‑2 CC BY‑NC 4.0). No protected health information is re‑identified. For the FracEye‑Public release, we will:

· Not redistribute raw images if the original license prohibits it; instead, release only the precomputed \phi features and labels.
· Include a data use agreement that prohibits re‑identification attempts.
· Ensure that any derived features are aggregated at a level that prevents inversion to original images.

