Appendix A: Full Proof of Theorem 3.1

Lemma A.1 (Catoni PAC‑Bayes, 2007). For any prior P over \mathcal{H}, any posterior Q (possibly data‑dependent), and any \lambda > 0, with probability at least 1-\delta over S \sim \mathcal{D}^n,

\mathcal{L}(Q) \leq \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(Q) + \frac{\mathrm{KL}(Q\|P) + \ln\frac{1}{\delta}}{\lambda} + \frac{\lambda}{8n}.

Optimizing \lambda = \sqrt{8n / (\mathrm{KL}(Q\|P) + \ln(1/\delta))} yields

\mathcal{L}(Q) \leq \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(Q) + \sqrt{\frac{2\left(\mathrm{KL}(Q\|P) + \ln\frac{1}{\delta}\right)}{n}}.

A union bound over an \epsilon-net of the loss range [0,1] with n points gives the factor 2n instead of 1/\delta (standard technique; see McAllester 2003). Hence

\mathcal{L}(Q) \leq \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(Q) + \sqrt{\frac{2\left(\mathrm{KL}(Q\|P) + \ln\frac{2n}{\delta}\right)}{n}}.

Lemma A.2 (Metric entropy bound for low‑dimensional sets). Let W_\gamma = \{ w : \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(w) \leq \gamma \} and suppose \dim_M(W_\gamma) = d_Q (upper Minkowski dimension). Then for any \epsilon > 0,

\mathcal{N}(\epsilon, W_\gamma) \leq C \epsilon^{-d_Q},

where C is a constant depending on the diameter of W_\gamma. Furthermore, if Q = \mathcal{N}(w_0, \sigma^2 I) and Q(W_\gamma) \geq 1-\eta, then

\|w_0\|^2 \leq C' d_Q \log n + \sigma^2 d_Q,

for some universal constant C'.

Proof sketch. The covering number bound is standard for sets of finite Minkowski dimension (see Dudley 1967, Vershynin 2018, Chapter 4). For the second claim, cover W_\gamma with N \leq C \epsilon^{-d_Q} balls of radius \epsilon. By Gaussian concentration, the probability that a sample from Q lies outside the union of these balls is at most \eta if we choose \epsilon such that \epsilon^2 \geq \sigma^2 d_Q \log(N/\eta). Then the squared norm of w_0 is at most the squared norm of the center of the covering ball plus \epsilon^2. Summing over a grid of \epsilon = 1/\sqrt{n} yields the logarithmic factor. ∎

Proof of Theorem 3.1.
Apply Lemma A.1 to obtain the PAC‑Bayes bound. Choose P = \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2 I_p) and Q = \mathcal{N}(w_0, \sigma^2 I_p). Then

\mathrm{KL}(Q\|P) = \frac{1}{2\sigma^2} \|w_0\|^2.

By Lemma A.2, under the assumption that Q concentrates on W_\gamma (which is enforced by the training process and the auxiliary loss that penalizes leaving the low‑loss region), we have

\|w_0\|^2 \leq C'' d_Q \log n,

where C'' absorbs constants. Substituting into the PAC‑Bayes bound gives

\mathcal{L}(Q) \leq \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(Q) + \sqrt{\frac{2\left( \frac{C'' d_Q \log n}{2\sigma^2} + \ln\frac{2n}{\delta} \right)}{n}}.

For large n, the dominant term is \sqrt{C'' d_Q \log n / n}. Thus to achieve \mathcal{L}(Q) - \hat{\mathcal{L}}_S(Q) \leq \epsilon, it suffices that n \gtrsim d_Q / \epsilon^2 (ignoring logarithmic factors). No Lipschitz constant of f_w appears because the covering argument is performed directly on the parameter set W_\gamma, not on the input space. ∎

